#compdef icon-gen
# =============================================================================
# icon-gen — Akabeko's "Generate an icon files from the SVG
#            or PNG files" — a TypeScript-Node CLI for
#            generating multi-platform icon files from a
#            single source SVG (or PNG directory).  Produces:
#              * .ico (Windows icon, multiple PNG sizes)
#              * .icns (macOS icon, multiple PNG sizes)
#              * Favicon PNG + ICO collection
#            All sizes configurable; uses Sharp (libvips) for
#            high-quality image rasterization + resizing.
#            Distinguishing from ImageMagick, png2icns, iconutil
#            (macOS stdlib), and other icon generators by:
#              - SINGLE-INPUT MULTI-OUTPUT — one SVG generates
#                Windows .ico + macOS .icns + Favicon PNGs +
#                Favicon .ico from a single command
#              - 3 OUTPUT FORMATS via --ico / --icns / --favicon
#                flags:
#                  * --ico       — Windows ICO with embedded PNGs
#                                  (default sizes: 16, 24, 32,
#                                   48, 64, 128, 256)
#                  * --icns      — macOS ICNS with embedded PNGs
#                                  (default sizes: 16, 32, 64,
#                                   128, 256, 512, 1024)
#                  * --favicon   — Web favicon set:
#                                   - favicon-16.png
#                                   - favicon-32.png
#                                   - favicon-128.png
#                                   - favicon.ico (multi-size)
#              - CONFIGURABLE SIZES per format via --ico-sizes /
#                --icns-sizes / --favicon-png-sizes /
#                --favicon-ico-sizes — comma-separated PNG
#                pixel sizes:
#                  icon-gen -i src.svg -o dist --ico-sizes 16,32,48,64
#              - DEFAULT BEHAVIOR — if no format flags
#                specified, generates ALL THREE formats with
#                default sizes (one-command "generate everything")
#              - SHARP LIBVIPS RASTERIZATION — uses lovell/
#                sharp (libvips bindings) for high-quality SVG-
#                to-PNG conversion at multiple sizes (libvips
#                handles SVG via librsvg)
#              - COMMANDER CLI — uses tj/commander.js for
#                argument parsing
#              - REPORT MODE via -r/--report — show processing
#                progress for each file generated
#              - PNG DIRECTORY INPUT — alternative to SVG:
#                provide a directory of pre-rendered PNGs at
#                each target size; icon-gen packages them
#                into .ico / .icns containers
#              - CUSTOM NAMES via --ico-name / --icns-name /
#                --favicon-name — override default output
#                file basenames
#              - LIBVIPS THROUGHPUT — sharp's libvips backend
#                processes images ~10x faster than pure-JS
#                alternatives (jimp); critical when generating
#                10-20 sizes for a single icon
#            Used by: Electron + Tauri + Wails desktop-app
#            developers preparing icons for cross-platform
#            release, Web teams generating favicon sets from a
#            single SVG asset, and as a reference
#            implementation of sharp + commander + Node.js
#            child-process composition in TypeScript-Node CLIs.
#
# Author:  Akabeko (akabekobeko on GitHub, http://akabeko.me)
#          — Japanese Node.js + Electron developer.  Released
#          ~2014; current version 5.0.0; active development
#          through 2026.  License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/akabekobeko/npm-icon-gen
#          https://github.com/akabekobeko/npm-icon-gen/blob/master/src/bin/cli.ts
#          https://github.com/akabekobeko/npm-icon-gen/blob/master/package.json
# CLI:     src/bin/cli.ts — uses tj/commander.js for argv
#          parsing.  Headline library: **sharp** (the new
#          variant being documented here, completing Axis 22
#          three-language symmetry across Rust / Go / TS-Node).
# Library: sharp (https://github.com/lovell/sharp —
#          "High performance Node.js image processing, the
#           fastest module to resize JPEG, PNG, WebP, AVIF and
#           TIFF images.  Uses the libvips library." — Lovell
#           Fuller (lovell on GitHub).  Distinct from image-rs/
#           image (R677, Rust Axis 22 opener) and disintegration/
#           imaging (R678, Go Axis 22 expansion) by being:
#              1. LIBVIPS BINDINGS — sharp wraps libvips
#                 (https://libvips.github.io/libvips/), a
#                 streaming + threading C image library written
#                 by John Cupitt + Kleis Auke Wolthuizen.
#                 libvips uses demand-driven processing:
#                 operations form a pipeline + execute lazily
#                 on read access, with parallelism + low memory
#                 footprint.  Distinct from image-rs/image
#                 (pure Rust) and disintegration/imaging
#                 (pure Go) which both load full images into
#                 RAM.
#              2. ~10x FASTER THAN PURE-JS ALTERNATIVES —
#                 libvips's streaming + SIMD + multithreading
#                 makes sharp the fastest Node.js image-
#                 processing module, particularly for large
#                 images.  Distinct from jimp (pure-JS,
#                 slower) and canvas (HTML5 Canvas API via
#                 Cairo, slower).
#              3. PROMISE-BASED ASYNC API — all sharp
#                 operations return Promises:
#                   import sharp from 'sharp';
#                   await sharp('input.jpg')
#                     .resize(800, 600, { fit: 'cover' })
#                     .rotate(90)
#                     .grayscale()
#                     .toFile('output.png');
#                 Distinct from image-rs/image (sync) and
#                 disintegration/imaging (sync).  Async fits
#                 Node.js's event-loop architecture for
#                 concurrent image processing.
#              4. PIPELINE OPERATIONS — sharp chains operations
#                 into a libvips pipeline; image is only
#                 decoded once and operations execute lazily:
#                   sharp('photo.jpg')
#                     .resize(800)         // queued
#                     .blur(5)             // queued
#                     .composite([...])    // queued
#                     .png()               // queued
#                     .toBuffer();         // executes pipeline
#                 Distinct from image-rs/image + imaging
#                 which immediately materialize each operation.
#              5. STREAMING via Stream API — sharp can read
#                 from + write to Node streams:
#                   inputStream.pipe(sharp().resize(800).png()).pipe(outputStream);
#                 Useful for HTTP request body → resize → S3
#                 upload pipelines (Vercel Edge, AWS Lambda).
#              6. 50+ OPERATIONS — resize (with 9 fit modes:
#                 cover, contain, fill, inside, outside),
#                 rotate, flip, flop, sharpen, blur, gamma,
#                 normalize, negate, threshold, boolean, modulate,
#                 tint, greyscale, removeAlpha, ensureAlpha,
#                 extractChannel, joinChannel, bandbool,
#                 composite (overlay with 30+ blend modes),
#                 extend (add borders), extract (crop), trim
#                 (auto-trim), median (median filter), recomb
#                 (color matrix), affine (geometric transform),
#                 clahe (contrast-limited adaptive histogram
#                 equalization), convolve (custom kernel), text
#                 (rasterize text), pipelineColourspace.
#              7. FORMAT-SPECIFIC OPTIONS — output configuration:
#                   .jpeg({ quality: 80, progressive: true, ... })
#                   .png({ compressionLevel: 9, palette: true })
#                   .webp({ quality: 80, effort: 6, smartSubsample: true })
#                   .avif({ quality: 50, effort: 4 })
#                   .tiff({ compression: 'lzw' })
#                   .heif({ quality: 50, compression: 'av1' })
#              8. PROBE IMAGE METADATA — `.metadata()` returns
#                 width, height, format, channels, depth, density,
#                 chromaSubsampling, isProgressive, hasProfile,
#                 hasAlpha, orientation, exif, icc, iptc, xmp.
#              9. LIBVIPS PREBUILT BINARIES — npm install
#                 sharp downloads platform-specific libvips
#                 prebuilt binary (Linux, macOS, Windows on
#                 x64/arm64).  No local libvips installation
#                 needed in typical use.
#             10. LOVELL-FULLER / sharp ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE —
#                 Lovell Fuller (lovell on GitHub) is a UK-
#                 based Node.js + image-processing expert.
#                 Sharp's success has spawned an ecosystem of
#                 sharp-* plugins (sharp-bmp, sharp-ico, sharp-
#                 multi-icon, sharp-multiformat, etc.).
#                 Lovell maintains sharp full-time supported by
#                 corporate sponsors (Cloudflare, Vercel, etc.).)
# License: Apache-2.0 (sharp); MIT (icon-gen)
# Status:  sharp — 32,276+ stars on lovell/sharp, ~70M weekly
#          npm downloads (TOP-30 npm package by downloads);
#          foundational image-processing library used by:
#            * Next.js Image Optimization
#            * Vercel Edge Image Optimization
#            * Cloudflare Image Resizing (some pipelines)
#            * Squoosh (Google's image-compression PWA)
#            * Sanity.io (headless CMS)
#            * Strapi (headless CMS)
#            * Payload CMS
#            * Ghost CMS (image processing)
#            * Hexo (Node blog framework — some plugins)
#            * @sanity/cli
#            * imagemin family (image-min-cli)
#            * sharp-cli (CLI wrapper)
#            * formidable (form parsing — image attachments)
#            * multer-sharp-s3
#            * icon-gen (THIS)
#            * 100,000+ npm packages
